@goerz So, I fiddled around a bit. I have found a way which I think will work.
Basically, what we will do is save all the @meta flags in data attribute of a div element. Something like below,
<div data-docstringscollapsed="true"></div>
Then add a js script, which will perform the necessary actions for each flags. For example, like this
// assets/html/js/metadata.js

// libraries: jquery
// arguments: $

let docstringscollapsed = $("div[data-docstringscollapsed]").data();

if (docstringscollapsed) {
  $("#documenter-article-toggle-button").click();
}
Doing this will always ensure that, all the scripts and DOM content will be loaded. Hence, it might mitigate what we are currently facing.
